1 Data

Presentation

For this exercise, we will use the data diamonds from the package ggplot2. A detailed description of these data can be found here.

First, run the following command to take a random subsample of size 400 from the original sample that contains more than 50000 observations:

set.seed(10)
diamonds2 <- diamonds[sample(nrow(diamonds), size = 400), ]

Change the default ggplot theme to bw. Set this globally for your entire R session.

2 Scatter plot

easy one

  1. Generate a scatter plot of price (y) versus carat (x), make the points bigger by setting size to 2. Save your plot into an R object (call it p1 for example).
p1 <- ggplot(diamonds2) +
  aes(x = carat, y = price) +
  geom_point(size = 2)
p1

blue

  1. Color all the points in blue.
ggplot(diamonds2) +
  aes(x = carat, y = price) +
  geom_point(size = 2, color = "blue")

map color on variable

  1. Extending the plot from question 1 (i.e., using the object p1), map the color of the points to the variable cut. Use geom_rug to visualize the marginal distributions of the two variables (carat and price). Also, add a legend at the top of your plot and set its title to Cut quality.
p1 <- ggplot(diamonds2) +
  aes(x = carat, y = price) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
# on ajoute a 
  aes(col = cut) +
  geom_rug(aes(col = NULL), alpha = 0.2) +
  theme(legend.position = "top") +

p1

6 different models regression

exp

  1. Extending the plot from question 1 (with the full original data), overlay 2 least-square lines on top of your scatter plot: one corresponding to \(y \sim x\) and the second corresponding to \(y \sim \exp(x)\). Your plot should look like this. Hint: use geom_smooth with the argument formula.
p1 +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, aes(col = "y~x")) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ exp(x), se = FALSE, aes(col = "y~exp(x)")) +
  labs(col = "Method")

8 Comparison with other function

add a normal density

  1. We would like to examine the distribution of \(log(price)\). More precisely, we would like to see, graphically, if a normal assumption is reasonable. To do so, you are asked to overlay a normal density curve (with the empirical mean and the empirical standard deviation) to the histogram of this variable. The resulting figure should look like this.
lprice <- log(diamonds2$price)
m.lprice <- mean(lprice)
s.lprice <- sd(lprice)
lpbreaks <- lprice |> pretty(nclass.Sturges(lprice))

ggplot(diamonds2) +
  aes(x = log(price)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), fill = "gray", alpha = 0.8, col = "white", breaks = lpbreaks) +
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, aes(y = log(price)), args = list(mean = m.lprice, sd = s.lprice), xlim = c(5.5, 10)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = lpbreaks) +
  labs(x = "Logarithm of the price", y = "Density", title = "Histogram of the logarithm of price \n together with the adjusted Normal density (black curve)")

add normal CDF

  1. The same question as before but, this time, use the cumulative distribution function (CDF) instead of the density. Hint: Use the ggplot2 function stat_ecdf().
ggplot(diamonds2) +
  aes(x = log(price)) +
  stat_ecdf(geom = "step", col = "red") +
  stat_function(fun = pnorm, aes(y = log(price)), args = list(mean = m.lprice, sd = s.lprice)) +
  labs(x = "Logarithm of the price", y = "CDF", title = "Empirical CDF of the logarithm of price \n together with the adjusted Normal CDF (black curve)")

10 truc trop beau

  1. Use the functions ggplot::geom_qq() and ggplot::geom_qq_line() and the package patchwork to produce a single plot that shows a box-plot, a density-plot and a qq-plot of price by cut.
p22.a <- ggplot(diamonds2, aes(x = cut, y = price, col = cut)) +
  geom_boxplot(varwidth = TRUE, size = 1, outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.2) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

p22.b <- ggplot(diamonds2, aes(x = price, fill = cut, col = cut)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.1, size = 1)

p22.c <- ggplot(diamonds2, aes(sample = price, col = cut), size = 2) +
  geom_qq() +
  geom_qq_line() +
  facet_grid(cols = vars(cut), labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

((p22.a + p22.b) / p22.c) + plot_layout(guides = "collect")
